  "prompt": "When should we change dusk brakes?",
  "response": "It's important to maintain your vehicle's brake system for safety and performance. Here are some signs that indicate it may be time to change your disc brakes:\n\n1. **Squeaking or Squealing Noise**: If you hear a high-pitched noise when you apply the brakes, it could mean that the brake pads are worn down and need replacement.\n\n2. **Grinding Sound**: If you hear a grinding noise, it usually means the brake pads are completely worn down, and the metal of the brake calipers is scraping against the disc rotor. This can cause serious damage and should be addressed immediately.\n\n3. **Vibration or Pulsation**: If you feel a vibration or pulsation in the brake pedal when applying the brakes, it could indicate warped rotors, which may require either resurfacing or replacement.\n\n4. **Brake Warning Light**: If the brake warning light on your dashboard illuminates, it\u2019s a sign to get your brakes checked right away.\n\n5. **Reduced Brake Performance**: If you notice that your car takes longer to stop or the brakes feel less responsive, it may be time to inspect and possibly replace the brake components.\n\n6. **Thickness of Brake Pads**: Most brake pads have a wear indicator that will make a noise when the pads are worn down to a certain level. If you\u2019re unsure, visually checking the brake pads can help; if they appear to be less than 1/4 inch thick, it\u2019s time to replace them.\n\n7. **Pulling to One Side**: If your vehicle pulls to one side when you apply the brakes, this can indicate uneven wear or a problem with your brake system.\n\n8. **Mileage Recommendations**: Many manufacturers recommend inspecting brake pads every 15,000 to 30,000 miles, but this can vary based on driving habits and conditions. Always refer to your vehicle's owner manual for specific recommendations.\n\nIf you experience any of these symptoms, it's a good idea to have your brakes inspected by a qualified mechanic. Regular maintenance is key to ensuring your vehicle is safe and performs well.",
